<DOC><DOCNO> AP891128-0184 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 0115EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Brady     11-28 0178</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Brady,0186</SECOND><HEAD>Treasury Secretary To Undergo Hip Surgery</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F.Brady, who hasbeen plagued in recent months by arthritis, will undergo electivesurgery on Dec. 14 to replace his right hip, the TreasuryDepartment announced.   The surgery, to be performed in an undisclosed location, hasbeen planned for a long time, said a department official whodeclined to be identified. Recovery should take three to six weeks,he said Monday.   Deputy Secretary John Robson will serve as acting secretary,Brady said in a memo to top department officials.   Despite his absence until mid-January, Brady will remain intouch with Treasury officials and take part in major decisions justhas he does when traveling outside the capital, the departmentofficial said.   With then-Vice President Bush's support, Brady was namedTreasury secretary in August 1988, succeeding James A. Baker III inthe final five months of the Reagan administration after Bakerresigned to head Bush's presidential campaign.   As expected, Bush kept Brady, a close friend and political ally,in the post after his election.</TEXT></DOC>